Crate root for `steno`, the compiler that turns steno-theory source (`.steno`/`dict.steno`) into Plover JSON dictionaries and LSP snippet artifacts. This file itself contains no logic — it only declares the module tree and re-exports the public API — but it is the map of the whole crate's pipeline and the place to look when unsure which module owns a given type or function.

The pipeline is strictly one-way: `parse` (fenced source → entry AST) → `expand` (fan-out counts, type-append chains, one-liner variants) → `render` (Plover dicts in plain/smart profiles, LSP snippets, `@literal` structural blocks). Each stage's output feeds only the next; nothing loops back. Every fallible operation returns one of the typed errors from `error` (`ExpandError`, `RenderError`, `SnippetError`, `StenoError`, `StrokeError`), and errors carry a 1-based source line number where applicable — callers matching on line numbers should not off-by-one adjust.

File I/O is deliberately excluded from the library: output is written only by the `build-dict`, `build-nvim`, and `measure` binaries elsewhere in the workspace, so adding a `write`/`save` function here would break that separation and should go in a binary crate instead.

Module responsibilities, per re-export list: `stroke` handles raw chord parsing/rendering and key ordering (`LEFT_ORDER`/`MID_ORDER`/`RIGHT_ORDER`, `KeySet`, `CountBank`/`CountBit` for numeric counting strokes); `parse` builds the `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr` AST from source text; `expand` turns parsed entries into `ExpandedEntry`/`TypedEntry` via type sets (`TypeDef`, `TypeOptions`, `TypeSet`) and count/flag expansion, with `ITERATION_BASE` governing count fan-out numbering; `render` produces `BuildResult` and the plain/smart dictionary builders; `editor` models cursor/keystroke behavior for smart-editor entries (`EditorState`, `Event`, `Behaviors`, with `PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT` presets and `INDENT_UNIT`); `snippet` builds LSP snippet output with `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` markers used to delimit tab-stop regions; `blocks` emits `@literal` structural text (`struct_text`, `emit_struct`); `json_out` provides `OrderedMap` and `to_json` for deterministic (insertion-order) JSON serialization, used instead of a standard map to keep dictionary output diffs stable.

Anything consuming this crate should import from the re-exports here rather than reaching into submodules directly, since submodule paths aren't part of the stable surface.